{"id": "23821", "post": "<div class=\"post-23821 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-tutorials tag-emergency tag-linux tag-linux-password-reset tag-password tag-rescue tag-sysadmin tag-tutorial\" id=\"post-23821\"><h2 class=\"storytitle\"><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/resetting-that-linux-root-password-you-forgot/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Resetting that Linux Root Password You Forgot</a></h2><div class=\"meta\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"/media/icons/tag_green.png\" data-src=\"/media/icons/tag_green.png\" alt=\"Tags: \" class=\"litespeed-loaded\" data-was-processed=\"true\"> <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/emergency/\" rel=\"tag\">emergency</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/linux/\" rel=\"tag\">linux</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/linux-password-reset/\" rel=\"tag\">linux password reset</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/password/\" rel=\"tag\">password</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/rescue/\" rel=\"tag\">rescue</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/sysadmin/\" rel=\"tag\">sysadmin</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/tutorial/\" rel=\"tag\">tutorial</a> <img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/media/icons/calendar.png\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/media/icons/calendar.png\" alt=\"Date/Time: \" class=\"litespeed-loaded\" data-was-processed=\"true\"> December 5, 2020 @ 12:00 am, by raindog308</div><div class=\"storycontent tablelook\"><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/lowendtutorial.png\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/lowendtutorial.png.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3957 litespeed-loaded\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/lowendtutorial.png.webp\" alt=\"lowendtutorial\" width=\"271\" height=\"70\" data-was-processed=\"true\"></a></p><p>You had to type it twice. You were supposed to put it in your password safe. You were going to setup sudo but didn\u2019t get a chance. You know it\u2019s something to do with a Scooby Doo cartoon and that one blues band you like but now you just can\u2019t remember your Linux root password.</p><p>Fear not, intrepid admin, there are ways to recover it. In this tutorial we\u2019ll walk you through recovering your root password on Linux.</p><h1>The Easy Ways</h1><p>If you have an account that can su to a shell, you can easily run \u201cpasswd root\u201d and reset it. Problem solved.</p><p>Depending on the virtualization and panel, you may be able to reset it from inside your provider\u2019s panel. This is universal with OpenVZ and some of the larger players (Vultr, Dropbox, Linode, etc.)</p><p>If these aren\u2019t options for you, we\u2019ll do it the old fashioned way.</p><p><span id=\"more-23821\"></span></p><h1>The Less Easy Way</h1><p>You\u2019ll need to mount a CD and reboot. In times past you had to use a rescue CD (or boot your installation media in rescue mode) but we\u2019ll show you how to do this via grub.</p><p>I\u2019m using a VPS at BuyVM, so the screenshots here will be for the Stallion panel, but they\u2019re very similar for Solus, etc.</p><p>I\u2019ve reinstalled a clean copy of Debian 10 on a VPS named oops.lowend.party. I\u2019ll boot it and then login. Now I\u2019ll reset it to something quite random:</p><pre>root@localhost:~# echo $RANDOM$RANDOM$RANDOM$RANDOM\n271201341711691335\nroot@localhost:~# passwd root\nNew password: (copied and pasted from above)\nRetype new password: \npasswd: password updated successfully\nroot@localhost:~#</pre><p>I didn\u2019t write the random string down so I have no idea what the password is.</p><p>Next I mounted the Debian 10 x64 CD. Then I changed the boot order so that CDs boot first:</p><p><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1.png.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-23822 litespeed-loaded\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"178\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1.png.webp 800w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1-300x67.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1-768x171.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1.png.webp 800w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1-300x67.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-1-768x171.png.webp 768w\" data-was-processed=\"true\"></p><p>Now I will launch the console and then reboot.</p><p><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI4MDAiIGhlaWdodD0iNjA0IiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgODAwIDYwNCI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-23823\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-2.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"604\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-2.png.webp 800w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-2-300x227.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-2-768x580.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"></p><p>When the GRUB bootloader appears, hit the down arrow to move on to \u201cAdvanced options for Debian GNU/Linux\u201d, then hit Enter.</p><p><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI4MDAiIGhlaWdodD0iNjAyIiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgODAwIDYwMiI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-23824\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-3.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"602\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-3.png.webp 800w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-3-300x226.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-3-768x578.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"></p><p>Now press \u2018e\u2019 for edit. You need to make two changes highlighted below on the line that begins with \u201clinux /boot/vmlinuz\u2026\u201d. You can use your arrow keys to move the cursor.</p><p>(1) change the \u2018ro\u2019 parameter to \u2018rw\u2019<br>\n(2) add init=/bin/bash at the end</p><p><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI4MDAiIGhlaWdodD0iNTk5IiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgODAwIDU5OSI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-23825\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-4.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"599\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-4.png.webp 800w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-4-300x225.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-4-768x575.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"></p><p><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI4MDAiIGhlaWdodD0iNTk4IiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgODAwIDU5OCI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-23827\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-5-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"598\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-5-1.png 800w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-5-1-300x224.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-5-1-768x574.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"></p><p>Then hit control-X to save and boot.</p><p>Linux will boot and you will come to a shell prompt. Enter the following command to mount your root filesystem:</p><pre>mount -n -o remount,rw /</pre><p>Then set the root password:</p><pre>passwd root</pre><p>Note: You may see a lot of \u201cvisual noise\u201d \u2013 log messages that suddenly appear on the screen. Ignore these because they are not being interpreted in what you type.</p><p>Once you\u2019re done, type the following to reboot</p><pre>exec /sbin/init</pre><p>Then upon reboot, I was able to login with the new root password I\u2019d set.</p><p><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI4MDAiIGhlaWdodD0iMjc2IiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgODAwIDI3NiI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-23828\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-6.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"276\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-6.png.webp 800w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-6-300x104.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/root-pw-6-768x265.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"></p><p>&nbsp;</p><div class=\"relpost-thumb-wrapper\"><div class=\"relpost-thumb-container\"><h3>Related posts:</h3><div style=\"clear: both\"></div><div style=\"clear: both\"></div><div class=\"relpost-block-container\"><a class=\"relpost-block-single\" href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/managing-your-lowendempire-with-ansible-part-1/\"><div style=\"width: 150px; height: 215px;\"><div class=\"relpost-block-single-image\" alt=\"Managing Your LowEndEmpire With Ansib